  "text": "Studies with isoflurane support the notion that the PRF is also an important site of anesthetic action. Isoflurane decreased GABA levels in the PRF [CITATION_1] . Behaviorally, the GABA A antagonist bicuculline injected into the PRF prolonged isoflurane-induced hypnosis [32 • ]. Similarly, pharmacologic administration into the PRF of an agent that decreased GABA levels decreased the time needed for isoflurane to induce loss of righting reflex; the opposite effect was observed after administration of an agent that increased GABA levels in the PRF [CITATION_2] .",
